imate position of ''Creekirk''{{'}}s wreck }}
'''SS ''Creekirk''''' was a cargo [[steamship]] that was built in [[Scotland]] in 1912 and sunk with all hands by a German submarine in 1940. At her launch in 1912 she was named '''SS ''Mariston'''''. In her 28-year career she was renamed '''SS ''Milcovul''''' in 1913, '''SS ''Hyphaestos''''' in 1933 and SS ''Creekirk'' in 1938.<ref name=LR38/>
==Building and first owner== Robert Duncan and Company of [[Port Glasgow]] built the ship for W.S. Miller's Ellaston Steam Ship Company<ref name=Mariners> {{cite web |url = http://www.mariners-list.com/site_pages.php?section=Shipping+Companies&category=Scottish&page_name=W.+S.+Miller+%26+Co |last1 = Mapplebeck |first1 = L Ron |last2 = O'Rourke |first2 = Mick |title = W. S. Miller & Co / Ellaston SS Co, Glasgow. |work = Shipping Companies |publisher = Mariners-List |accessdate = 15 July 2013 |ref = harv }}</ref> of Glasgow and completed her as ''Mariston'' in 1912.<ref name=LR38/> She had six corrugated furnaces with a combined grate area of {{convert|130|sqft|0}} that heated two 180 [[Pounds per square inch|lb<sub>f</sub>/in<sup>2</sup>]] single-ended boilers with a combined heating surface of {{convert|5384|sqft|0}}.<ref name=LR38/> These fed one three-cylinder [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|triple-expansion steam engine]] built by Rankin and Blackmore of [[Greenock]].<ref name=LR38/> Her engine drove a single [[Propeller (marine)|screw]] and was rated at 338 [[Horsepower#Nominal horsepower|NHP]].<ref name=LR38/>
==Changes of owner and name== In 1913 ''Mariston''{{'}}s owners sold her to Romania Prima Naţională de Navigație Maritimă,<ref name=Mariners/> who renamed her ''Milcovul'' and registered her in [[Port of Brăila|Brăila]]<ref name=LR30/> on the River [[Danube]]. In August 1916 Romania entered the First World War, and by the end of the year ''Milcovul'' had been requisitioned as a transport ship for the [[Imperial Russian Navy]].<ref name=Mariners/> In 1918 [[German Empire]] forces captured her but that November the [[Central Powers]] [[Armistice with Germany|conceded defeat]] to the [[Allies of World War I|Entente Powers]] and ''Milcovul''{{'}}s owners recovered her.<ref name=Mariners/>
''Milcovul'' was in Romania Prima Naţională de Navigație Maritimă's fleet for two decades. When the Russian émigré Alexandre Vlasov took over the company in 1933, ''Milcovul'' was sold to Ant. G. Yannoulatos and Sons, who renamed her ''Hyphaestos'' and registered her in [[Port of Piraeus|Piraeus]].<ref name=LR35/> Yannoulatos ran ''Hyphaestos'' for five years and then sold her in 1938 to the Cree Steam Ship Company Ltd of London.<ref name=LR38/> Cree renamed the ship ''Creekirk'', registered her in [[Port of London|London]] and appointed Muir, Young Ltd to manage her.<ref name=LR38/>
==Convoy SC-7 and loss== In autumn 1940 ''Creekirk'' loaded 5,900 tons of iron ore at [[Wabana, Newfoundland and Labrador|Wabana]] and [[Conception Bay]] in [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] and then sailed to [[Sydney, Nova Scotia]].<ref name=U609/> There she joined [[Convoy SC-7]], which on 5 October sailed for [[Port of Liverpool|Liverpool]]. ''Creekirk'' was typical of SC 7's 35 merchant ships: old, slow (one source says she could manage only {{convert|8.5|kn|km/h}})<ref> {{cite web |url = http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?30794 |title = SS Creekirk [+1940] |last1 = Allen |first1 = Tony |last2 = Lettens |first2 = Jan |date = 18 October 2009 |work = WreckSite |publisher = wrecksite.eu |accessdate = 14 July 2013 |ref = harv }}</ref> and vulnerable. ''Creekirk'' had only one [[Defensively Equipped Merchant Ships|DEMS]] professional military gunner:<ref name=U609/> her armament would have been operated largely by members of her own [[Merchant Navy (United Kingdom)|Merchant Navy]] crew. At first the convoy had but one escort ship, the {{sclass-|Hastings|sloop}} {{HMS|Scarborough|L25|6}}.
On 16 October a [[Wolfpack (naval tactic)|wolf pack]] of [[U-boat]]s found SC 7 and quickly overwhelmed its inadequate defences. The attack continued for several days, and on 18 October it intensified as the number of U-boats increased. At 2112 hrs ''Creekirk'' was in the [[Western Approaches]] northwest of [[Rockall]] when [[Fritz Frauenheim]]'s {{GS|U-101|1940|2}} torpedoed her.<ref name=U609/> She sank quickly with the loss of all hands: her [[Sea captain|Master]] Elie Robilliard, 34 crew and her one DEMS gunner.<ref name=U609/>
